Friedman favored immigration, saying "legal and illegal immigration has a very positive impact on the U.S. economy."[110] However, he suggested that immigrants ought not to have access to the welfare system.[110] Friedman stated that immigration from Mexico had been a "good thing", in particular illegal immigration.[110] Friedman argued that illegal immigration was a boon because they "take jobs that most residents of this country are unwilling to take, they provide employers with workers of a kind they cannot get" and they do not use welfare.[110] In Free to Choose, Friedman wrote:[105]
